"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-9-10.py

Key context notes:
- Ch 9: post-exilic Jerusalem settlers (parallel to Neh 11); maʿal = unfaithfulness (v1, key Chronistic term)
- vv1-34 form the bridge between the genealogical prologue (chs 1-9) and the David narrative
- Nethinim (v2) = temple servants; appear only in Chr/Ezra/Neh
- Gatekeeper section (v17-27) elevated to major office; Phinehas establishes the precedent (v20)
- vv35-44 repeat 8:29-40 to bridge genealogy to Saul narrative
- Ch 10: Saul's death (= 1 Sam 31) + crucial editorial vv13-14 absent from Samuel
- maʿal (v13) = unfaithfulness/treachery — key Chronistic theological term (29x in Chronicles)
- ʾôḇ (v13) = medium/necromancer — consulting the dead instead of seeking YHWH
- dāraš YHWH (v14) = seek/inquire of the LORD — the defining Chronistic criterion for kingship
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The transitional verse of the entire genealogical prologue (chs. 1-9): <em>wîhûḏāh hoglᵉtāh lᵉḇāḇel bᵉmaʿlām</em> — &lsquo;and Judah was exiled to Babylon because of their unfaithfulness.&rsquo; The word <em>maʿal</em> (unfaithfulness, treachery, breach of covenant) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature theological term for apostasy (used 29 times in Chronicles vs. once in Samuel-Kings). The exile is not an accident or merely political defeat but the direct consequence of covenantal <em>maʿal</em>. The clause &lsquo;recorded in the Book of the Kings of Israel&rsquo; cites a now-lost royal annals source used by both Kings and Chronicles.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first resettlers of the land: <em>yiśrāʾēl hakkōhănîm halewîyim wᵉhannᵉtînîm</em> — Israelites, priests, Levites, and Nethinim (temple servants). The <strong>Nethinim</strong> (<em>nᵉtînîm</em> = given/dedicated ones) appear only in Chronicles, Ezra, and Nehemiah — they were hereditary temple servants, possibly descendants of Canaanite laborers conscripted by Solomon (Ezra 2:58) or of the Gibeonites (Josh 9:27). Their inclusion here shows the Chronicler&rsquo;s awareness of a diversified temple service community that included non-Israelite heritage groups.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jerusalem&rsquo;s post-exile population includes not just Judah and Benjamin but also <em>ûmibbᵉnê ʾep̄rayim ûmᵉnaššeh</em> (from the children of Ephraim and Manasseh) — northern tribal representatives in Jerusalem. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s all-Israel ideology applied to the resettlement: the city of David is not just southern but represents the whole covenant people. This list is closely parallel to Nehemiah 11:1-24, though with variant names; both appear to draw from the same administrative register of returnees.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Judahite settlers are listed in three sub-groups: the Perezite clan (Uthai son of Ammihud, v. 4), the Shelanite clan (Asaiah the firstborn, v. 5), and the Zerahite clan (Jeuel with 690 brothers, v. 6). These correspond to the three main Judahite sub-clans descending from Judah&rsquo;s sons: Perez (the royal line), Shelah, and Zerah. The parallel passage in Neh 11:4-6 has variant names, reflecting the difficulty of transmitting proper-name lists across generations.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Asaiah the firstborn of the Shelanite clan. The Shelanites are descendants of Judah&rsquo;s third son Shelah (Gen 38:5; 1 Chr 4:21-23). Their presence in the Jerusalem resettlement community shows the breadth of Judahite clans that returned from Babylon — not just the Davidic Perezites but all three of Judah&rsquo;s main lines.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The sons of Zerah — 690 brothers. Zerah was Judah&rsquo;s twin son by Tamar (Gen 38:30), whose descendants included the wise men Ethan, Heman, Calcol, and Dara (1 Kgs 4:31). The 690 figure represents the Zerahite resettlement community as a whole, not just this individual family. The Zerahites appear primarily in the Judahite genealogy of ch. 2 and in the context of Achan&rsquo;s sin (Josh 7:1).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Benjaminite settlers begin with Sallu son of Meshullam. Three Benjaminite clans are represented in vv. 7-9. Benjamin&rsquo;s prominent place in the Jerusalem resettlement reflects the tribe&rsquo;s geographical position: much of Benjaminite territory was immediately north of Jerusalem (Gibeon, Mizpah, Gibeah), and Benjamin had been given to Judah as a companion tribe (1 Kgs 12:21) after the split. The 956 Benjaminites total (v. 9) is smaller than Judah&rsquo;s numbers, showing Judah&rsquo;s numerical dominance in the restored community.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Two additional Benjaminite heads: Ibneiah son of Jeroham and Elah son of Uzzi (of Meshullam the son of Shephatiah). The complex patronymics here reflect the careful genealogical record-keeping of priestly and noble families during and after the exile. The Babylonian diaspora maintained these records precisely because family lineage determined eligibility for land, temple service, and Levitical roles after the return.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The summary of Benjaminite heads: 956 men. <em>ʾēlleh rāʾšê ʾāḇôt lᵉbêt ʾăḇôtām</em> — &lsquo;these were chief men of their fathers&rsquo; houses&rsquo; — the administrative formula showing these are the household heads, not a complete census. The Neh 11:7-8 parallel lists 928 Benjaminites, a minor discrepancy likely reflecting different points in time or different sources.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priestly resettlers begin: Jedaiah, Jehoiarib, Jachin. These are three of the twenty-four priestly divisions established by David (1 Chr 24:7-18). Their listing here shows the continuity of the priestly rotation system from David through the exile and into the restoration — the institution survived Babylon. Jehoiarib is the priestly division from which the Maccabees later came (1 Macc 2:1).</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>ʿăzaryāh ben-ḥilqiyyāh</strong> — Azariah son of Hilkiah. This is either Azariah the high priest (the Azariah who served during the early monarchy, 1 Kgs 4:2) or a later Azariah. <em>nāgîḏ bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm</em> — &lsquo;officer/ruler of the house of God&rsquo; — the title <em>nāgîḏ</em> (prince/overseer) for the temple administrator is rare; it parallels the civil <em>nāgîḏ</em> used for the king. The double leadership structure (civil governor + temple overseer) reflects the post-exilic reality where the high priest held both political and religious authority.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Adaiah son of Jeroham and Maasai son of Adiel — further priestly clans. The genealogies trace back to Immer (one of David&rsquo;s 24 priestly divisions, 1 Chr 24:14) and Malchijah (another priestly division, 24:9). The phrase &lsquo;very able men for the work of the service of the house of God&rsquo; (v. 13) applies the military language of <em>gibbôrê ḥayil</em> to priestly competence — professional excellence in temple service.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The priestly total: 1,760 men &lsquo;very capable in the work of the service of the house of God.&rsquo; The high number reflects the importance the Chronicler places on the priestly community — temple service requires a substantial professional corps. The Neh 11:10-14 parallel shows 1,192 priests, again a discrepancy between the two lists likely reflecting different periods or sources.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Levitical resettlers begin with Shemaiah son of Hasshub (Merarite line). The Levitical genealogies in the resettlement list correspond to the three great Levitical clans of Gershom, Kohath, and Merari established in the wilderness (Num 3). The Merarites were responsible for the heavier tabernacle frames and boards (Num 4:29-33); in the temple era their descendants serve in the gate-keeping and maintenance roles.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Bakbakkar, Heresh, Galal, and Mattaniah son of Micah (Asaphite lineage). Mattaniah&rsquo;s role as leader of <em>hayyāḏāh</em> (the thanksgiving/praise) ties directly to the Asaphite musician tradition. Asaph was one of David&rsquo;s three chief musicians (6:31-48); his descendants continued as temple singers through the exile and back into the restoration (Ezra 2:41; 3:10; Neh 11:17).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Obadiah son of Shemaiah (Jeduthunite lineage) and Berechiah son of Asa (who lived in the villages of the Netophathites). Netophah was near Bethlehem (Ezra 2:22); Levitical families settled in villages throughout Judah rather than being concentrated only in Jerusalem. The Jeduthunite musicians (cf. 6:44) maintained their tradition through this dispersed community.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The gatekeepers: Shallum, Akkub, Talmon, Ahiman, and their brothers — Shallum being the chief. <strong>Gatekeeping</strong> was a distinct Levitical office with its own hereditary guilds. The four men named here represent the four main gatekeeper clans; their descendants are listed among the returnees in Ezra 2:42 and Neh 7:45 (192 gatekeepers total). The gatekeepers controlled access to the temple courts, maintaining its holiness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The east gate — &lsquo;the king&rsquo;s gate&rsquo; (<em>šaʿar hammelek</em>) — was under the Levitical gatekeepers&rsquo; authority eastward. The eastern gate had special significance as the principal entrance to the temple mount; Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision associates the eastern gate with the divine glory (Ezek 43:1-4; 44:1-3). The &lsquo;companies of the Levites&rsquo; rotating through gate service maintained the 24-7 sacred boundary of the temple precinct.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shallum son of Kore son of Ebiasaph (Kohathite lineage) and his brothers — the &lsquo;sons of Korah&rsquo; over the threshold service. The Korahites are known primarily as the psalmist guild (Pss 42-49, 84-85, 87-88 are Korahite psalms), but their original role was gatekeeper-thresholder (Num 16:49 notwithstanding — the Korah lineage survived through Elkanah, 1 Chr 6:22-27). Their &lsquo;fathers&rsquo; had been responsible for the tabernacle entrance.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>wᵉpînᵉḥās ben-ʾelʿāzār nāgîḏ hāyāh ʿălêhem lip̄ānîm</strong> — &lsquo;And Phinehas son of Eleazar had been the ruler over them previously.&rsquo; Phinehas, the grandson of Aaron who &lsquo;turned away the wrath of God&rsquo; at Baal-Peor (Num 25:6-13) and received the covenant of a permanent priesthood (Num 25:12-13; Ps 106:30), serves as the historical precedent for gatekeeper authority. The Chronicler elevates gate-keeping by tracing it to this foundational moment of priestly zeal. <em>YHWH ʿimmô</em> — &lsquo;the LORD was with him&rsquo; — the divine-presence formula of legitimation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Zechariah son of Meshelemiah — porter of the door of the tent of meeting. This is a Kohathite/Korahite gatekeeper from the tabernacle era; the Chronicler uses his example to establish that the gatekeeping office goes back to the wilderness period, not just to David&rsquo;s reorganization. The continuity from tabernacle to temple is a recurring Chronistic theme.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>kull̄ām habbᵉrûrîm laššōʿărîm bassippîm mēʾatayim ûšnêm ʿāśār</strong> — 212 gatekeepers chosen for the threshold posts, enumerated in their villages. <em>hēmmāh dāwid ûšᵉmûʾēl hārōʾeh yissᵉḏām bᵉʾĕmûnātām</em> — &lsquo;David and Samuel the seer had appointed them in their trust.&rsquo; The joint authority of king and prophet (David and Samuel) establishing the gatekeeper guilds parallels the same double-authority pattern for the musicians (6:31). Samuel&rsquo;s involvement is not in Samuel-Kings; it&rsquo;s a Chronistic claim to deepen the office&rsquo;s legitimacy.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The gatekeepers and their children had oversight of the gates of the house of the LORD — the temple of the tent. <em>bêt YHWH lᵉbêt hāʾōhel</em> — &lsquo;the house of the LORD — even the tent-house&rsquo; — the Chronicler consistently identifies the temple as the permanent successor of the wilderness tabernacle. The architectural transition (tent → temple) does not interrupt the theological continuity of the divine dwelling.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The gatekeepers were stationed in four directions — east, west, north, south. The four-directional coverage symbolizes complete and universal guard of the sacred precinct. This organizational structure likely corresponds to the four sides of the temple complex, each with its own gate system. The Mishnah later describes a similar four-directional gatekeeper organization at the Second Temple (m. Middot).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Brothers from the villages rotating in seven-day terms. The weekly rotation system meant that Jerusalem&rsquo;s temple service was staffed by Levites from throughout the land, not just permanent Jerusalem residents. This distributed system kept the provincial Levitical communities connected to the central sanctuary — maintaining the all-Israel character of temple worship that Chronicles consistently emphasizes.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The four chief gatekeepers (<em>habbᵉrîrîm</em> — chosen ones) were permanently stationed, unlike the rotating brothers; they had charge of the chambers (<em>hališkôt</em>) and treasuries of the house of God. The temple complex included extensive storage facilities for tithes, offerings, and temple vessels. The gatekeepers&rsquo; responsibility for these rooms made them the de facto custodians of the temple&rsquo;s material resources.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The gatekeepers lodged round about the house of God — &lsquo;because upon them was the watch&rsquo; (<em>kî ʿălêhem hammišmeret</em>) &lsquo;and the opening thereof every morning&rsquo; (<em>ûlabbōqer labbōqer lāhem</em>). The ritual of opening the temple each morning was a significant liturgical act. The gatekeepers&rsquo; overnight presence ensured the temple was never left unguarded — the sacred space required continuous human stewardship.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Certain gatekeepers had charge of the ministering vessels — counting them in and out. The phrase <em>bᵉmispar yᵉḇîʾûm ûḇᵉmispar yôṣîʾûm</em> (by number bringing them in and by number taking them out) shows meticulous accountability for sacred objects. Temple vessels were precious both practically and theologically; the golden and silver vessels carried to Babylon (2 Chr 36:18; Ezra 1:7-11) were precisely those that post-exilic accountability sought to prevent from future loss.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Other Levites had oversight of the furnishings, holy vessels, fine flour, wine, oil, frankincense, and spices. The specialization of roles — gatekeepers, vessel-counters, supply managers, incense keepers — reflects a sophisticated temple administration. The mention of spices (<em>bᵉśāmîm</em>) and incense (<em>lᵉḇōnāh</em>) as separate categories reflects the complexity of the daily offering protocol (morning and evening incense, Exod 30:7-8).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Some of the sons of the priests prepared the ointment of spices (<em>rōqᵉḥê miqqaḥat habᵉśāmîm</em>). The preparation of the sacred anointing oil was a priestly specialty (Exod 30:25-33) — it could not be delegated to non-priests. This detail shows the Chronicler&rsquo;s careful distinction between priestly and Levitical roles within the temple service hierarchy.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Mattithiah, a Levite, the firstborn of Shallum the Korahite, <em>bᵉʾĕmûnāh</em> (in faithfulness/trust) over the flat cakes (<em>ḥăḇittîm</em>). The flat cakes/pancakes on the griddle were a daily offering (Lev 6:14-23). The Levitical assignment of specific food-preparation roles — baking, roasting — to hereditary families ensured consistent preparation of the daily offerings.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Others of the Kohathite brothers were over the showbread (<em>leḥem hammaʿreḵet</em>), setting it in order every Sabbath. The showbread (12 loaves representing the 12 tribes, Lev 24:5-9) was a permanent presence before YHWH, renewed weekly. Its preparation was a Kohathite specialty, linking this post-exilic practice back to the Kohathite musicians&rsquo; broader priestly role.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The singers, heads of fathers&rsquo; houses among the Levites, were free from other duties because they were employed in the work day and night. The exemption of musicians from other Levitical tasks shows the primacy of temple music in the Chronicler&rsquo;s worship theology. The &lsquo;day and night&rsquo; formula suggests a continuous cycle of praise — a proto-liturgy of the hours that later developed into continuous intercession traditions.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The chief Levitical fathers, head men, lived in Jerusalem. This summary (vv. 2-34) of the Jerusalem settler community provides the Chronicler&rsquo;s vision of the restored covenant community: a balanced hierarchy of priests, Levites, musicians, gatekeepers, and supply officers — the full institutional apparatus of temple worship intact and functioning, demonstrating YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to his people despite the exile.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The Gibeonite family of Jehiel reappears (see ch. 8:29-32 for nearly identical content). The repetition is deliberate: the Chronicler uses this genealogy as a literary bridge. The genealogical prologue (chs. 1-9) covered all Israel from Adam to the post-exilic community; now this family, which will produce Saul, transitions the reader from genealogy to narrative. The Gibeonites were David&rsquo;s subjects who were spared in Joshua&rsquo;s day (Josh 9), adding another all-Israel dimension.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jehiel&rsquo;s firstborn Abdon and his brothers: Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab. These are Saul&rsquo;s extended family. Ner is Saul&rsquo;s grandfather (Abner&rsquo;s father, 1 Sam 14:51), and Kish is Saul&rsquo;s father. The deliberate genealogical bridge here — placing Saul&rsquo;s family in the genealogical prologue — contextualizes Saul as a figure within all-Israel&rsquo;s covenant history before narrating his failure in ch. 10.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah, and Mikloth — Jehiel&rsquo;s other sons. These names are largely unattested elsewhere; the genealogy serves mainly as the literary link from Gibeon to Saul. Gibeon was the pre-Solomonic high place where YHWH appeared to Solomon (2 Chr 1:3-12), giving Gibeon continuing theological importance in the Chronicler&rsquo;s narrative.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Mikloth begat Shimeam, and they also lived in Jerusalem opposite their brothers. The note that this family lived in Jerusalem &lsquo;over against their brothers&rsquo; (<em>wᵉʾap-hēmmāh neged ʾăḥêhem yāšᵉḇû ḇîrûšālēm ʿim-ʾăḥêhem</em>) emphasizes the integration of all groups — Gibeonite/Benjaminite families and Levitical families — in the restored Jerusalem community.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Ner begat Kish; Kish begat Saul; Saul begat Jonathan, Malchishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal. Eshbaal (&lsquo;man of Baal&rsquo;) is the original name that 2 Sam 2:8 euphemistically changes to Ishbosheth (&lsquo;man of shame&rsquo;) by substituting <em>bōšet</em> (shame) for <em>baʿal</em>. The Chronicler preserves the original theophoric form, though the Baal-name is historically embarrassing — showing the pre-reform Israelite practice of using Baal as a divine title for YHWH before the Elijah-era condemnation of Baal worship.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Meribbaal son of Jonathan, who begat Micah. As in 8:34, the Chronicler uses Meribbaal (the original name, &lsquo;Baal contends/is great&rsquo;) rather than 2 Sam 9:6&rsquo;s Mephibosheth (&lsquo;from the mouth of shame&rsquo; — another euphemistic substitution). Meribbaal/Mephibosheth was the crippled son of Jonathan whom David showed kindness to (2 Sam 9) — a connection the Chronicler omits but the genealogy preserves by continuing Jonathan&rsquo;s line.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Sons of Micah: Pithon, Melech, Tahrea, and Ahaz. In 8:35, Ahaz appears instead of Tahrea at the same position — the two lists have minor variants at this point. Ahaz may have been the more prominent figure whose name was easier to remember, while Tahrea is otherwise unattested.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The Saulide line continues through Jarah (or Jehoaddah in 8:36 — a variant) and Zimri, Moza, and Azmaveth. These post-Saulide generations — living under Davidic rule — maintained their genealogical records even though the political dynasty had passed to Judah. The Chronicler preserves their line, showing respect for all Israelite lineages regardless of their relationship to power.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Moza → Binea → Rephaiah → Eleasah → Azel. In 8:37, Rapha appears instead of Rephaiah — another minor scribal variant. The six-generation descent from Moza reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s thoroughness in maintaining the Saulide genealogy well into the Davidic period.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Azel&rsquo;s six sons: Azrikam, Bocheru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, Hanan. This final entry of the genealogical prologue brings the Saulide line into the same general era as David&rsquo;s era. Chapter 10 immediately follows with Saul&rsquo;s death — the genealogy having established who he was and where he fit in Israel&rsquo;s story before narrating his end. The six-son conclusion mirrors the six-son conclusion of 8:38-39, confirming the genealogy is complete.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>1 Chronicles 10 is almost verbatim from 1 Samuel 31. But the Chronicler&rsquo;s use of it is radically selective: everything from 1 Samuel 1-30 (Samuel&rsquo;s career, Saul&rsquo;s rise, his conflicts with David, the Witch of Endor, David&rsquo;s Philistine alliance) is omitted. The Chronicler begins Israel&rsquo;s royal narrative at the moment of Saul&rsquo;s catastrophic defeat, treating it as the definitive statement of his reign before immediately transitioning to David. The battle of Mount Gilboa (in the Jezreel Valley) was one of the worst military defeats in Israel&rsquo;s history — the Philistines effectively controlled the central highlands after it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jonathan, Abinadab, and Malchishua — three of Saul&rsquo;s sons killed. The fourth son, Eshbaal (Ishbosheth), survived and would briefly rule north Israel under Abner&rsquo;s regency (2 Sam 2-4). The Chronicler omits Ishbosheth entirely, keeping his focus on the Davidic transition. Jonathan&rsquo;s death is particularly poignant given his covenant friendship with David (1 Sam 18:3; 20:42), though the Chronicler does not pause on this.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The archers (<em>môrîm baqqešet</em>) hit Saul and wounded him. In 1 Sam 31:3, the Hebrew is ambiguous between &lsquo;archers&rsquo; and &lsquo;shooters-with-the-bow&rsquo;; Chronicles uses the same phrasing. Saul&rsquo;s death-wound came from the anonymous Philistine archery — no individual hero kills Saul. The cowardly claim in 2 Sam 1:1-16 (the Amalekite who claimed credit) is omitted by Chronicles, keeping the narrative clean.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s request to his armor-bearer: <em>šᵉlōp̄ ḥarbekā ûdāqrēnî ḇāh</em> — &lsquo;draw your sword and run me through.&rsquo; Saul feared the uncircumcised Philistines would mock him (<em>wᵉhitʿallᵉlû-ḇî</em> — &lsquo;abuse/mock/triumph over me&rsquo;). His armor-bearer refused for fear. Saul fell on his own sword — suicide by falling on one&rsquo;s own weapon was the honorable death for a defeated king in the ANE, avoiding capture and degradation. The armor-bearer then did the same.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The armor-bearer dies alongside his master. The loyalty of the armor-bearer — choosing death over abandonment of the king — is a minor act of faithfulness that contrasts with the faithlessness the Chronicler will attribute to Saul (v. 13). Even in death, Saul&rsquo;s servant was more loyal than Saul was to YHWH.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>wayyāmot šāʾûl ûšᵉlōšet bānāyw ûkol-bêtô yaḥdāw mētû</strong> — &lsquo;So Saul and his three sons died, and all his house died together.&rsquo; The Chronicler expands 1 Sam 31:6 (&lsquo;and all his men&rsquo;) to &lsquo;all his house.&rsquo; This is the theological climax of Saul&rsquo;s narrative: the extinction of the Saulide ruling house. YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is total. In Chronicles, this verse marks the complete end of the Saulide dynasty — there is no space for Ishbosheth&rsquo;s brief counter-reign or David&rsquo;s loyalty to Jonathan&rsquo;s son.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The men of Israel in the valley and beyond the Jordan fled; the Philistines occupied the abandoned cities. This geographical note — valley + trans-Jordan — shows the scope of the military collapse. The Philistine occupation of Israelite cities was not just military defeat but territorial seizure, reverting the land to enemy hands. The phrase <em>wayyāḇōʾû pᵉlištîm wayyēšᵉḇû bāhem</em> (&lsquo;the Philistines came and dwelt in them&rsquo;) is the nadir — a reversal of the conquest.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The next day the Philistines found Saul&rsquo;s fallen body. <em>wayᵉpaššᵉṭû ʾet-haḥălālîm</em> — &lsquo;they stripped the slain.&rsquo; Stripping the dead was standard ANE battle practice — collecting armor, weapons, and valuables from fallen enemies. Finding the king&rsquo;s body was a major trophy. The Chronicler follows 1 Sam 31:8-10 closely here.</p>",
    "9": "<p>They stripped Saul and took his head and armor, sending messengers throughout Philistia to carry the news to their idols and their people. <em>lᵉḇaśśēr ʾet-ʿăṣabbêhem wᵉʾet-hāʿām</em> — &lsquo;to bring good news to their idols and to the people.&rsquo; The word <em>ʿăṣabbîm</em> (idols, literally &lsquo;labored things/grief-things&rsquo;) is a contemptuous term. Philistine victory was credited to their gods — especially Dagon. The news circuit paralleled Israel&rsquo;s own practice of celebrating YHWH&rsquo;s victories.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s armor was deposited in the house of their gods, and his head was fastened in the temple of Dagon. The trophy display of a defeated king in an enemy temple was an ANE practice of theological humiliation — demonstrating that the enemy&rsquo;s god had overcome the defeated nation&rsquo;s deity. The irony is sharp: YHWH had already demonstrated his superiority over Dagon when the ark was placed in Dagon&rsquo;s temple (1 Sam 5:1-5), and yet here YHWH&rsquo;s king&rsquo;s head adorns Dagon&rsquo;s temple. The Chronicler&rsquo;s vv. 13-14 will address this apparent theological reversal.</p>",
    "11": "<p>When the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead heard what the Philistines had done to Saul — all the valiant men arose and took Saul&rsquo;s body and his sons&rsquo; bodies and brought them to Jabesh. Jabesh-gilead had a special covenant relationship with Saul: he had rescued them in his first act as king (1 Sam 11) from Nahash the Ammonite. Their loyalty here — at great personal risk — fulfills the covenant debt. Even after Saul&rsquo;s death, his first act of royal faithfulness elicited this final act of human loyalty.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The valiant men of Jabesh brought the bodies, buried the bones under the oak in Jabesh, and fasted seven days. The seven-day mourning fast (<em>wayyāṣûmû šiḇʿat yāmîm</em>) was the full period of mourning (Gen 50:10). The burial &lsquo;under the oak&rsquo; in Jabesh was an honorable interment — the oak was a sacred tree associated with covenant (Gen 35:8; Josh 24:26). Chronicles omits the later detail of David recovering the bones for final burial at Zela (2 Sam 21:12-14).</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>wayyāmot šāʾûl bᵉmaʿlô ʾăšer māʿal baYHWH</strong> — &lsquo;So Saul died for his unfaithfulness (<em>maʿal</em>) which he committed against the LORD.&rsquo; This verse and v. 14 are the Chronicler&rsquo;s unique addition, absent from 1 Sam 31. Three specific offenses: (1) <em>māʿal baYHWH</em> — general unfaithfulness; (2) not keeping the word of YHWH (referring to 1 Sam 15, Saul&rsquo;s incomplete destruction of Amalek, which Chronicles has not narrated but assumes knowledge of); (3) <em>lišʾôl bāʾôḇ lᵉḏrōš</em> — consulting a medium to inquire. The medium (<em>ʾôḇ</em>) consultation (1 Sam 28) was explicitly forbidden (Lev 19:31; 20:6; Deut 18:11). Saul sought the dead instead of the Living God.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>wᵉlōʾ ḏāraš baYHWH wayyᵉmîtēhû wayyasēb ʾet-hammalḵût lᵉḏāwîḏ ben-yišay</strong> — &lsquo;and did not inquire of the LORD; therefore he killed him and turned the kingdom over to David son of Jesse.&rsquo; The verb <em>dāraš</em> (to seek, inquire of, resort to) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s central theological diagnostic for good kingship. Kings who seek (<em>dāraš</em>) the LORD prosper; those who do not are destroyed. This verse sets up the entire Davidic narrative that follows: David&rsquo;s characteristic quality will be exactly this seeking of the LORD. The kingdom transfer — <em>wayyasēb ʾet-hammalḵût</em> (he turned/transferred the kingdom) — is attributed directly to YHWH&rsquo;s action, not David&rsquo;s political maneuvering.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRON1)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles', existing)
    print('1 Chronicles 9-10 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
